===Grand final=== {{main|1991 AFL Grand Final}}
{{start box}} |- bgcolor="#CCCCFF" | '''Home team''' | '''Home team score''' | '''Away team''' | '''Away team score''' | '''Ground''' | '''Crowd''' | '''Date''' |- bgcolor="#FFFFFF" |'''{{AFL Haw}}'''|| '''20.19 (139)''' ||{{AFL WC}}|| 13.8 (86) ||[[Waverley Park]]|| 75,230 ||Saturday 28, September {{end box}}
==Ladder== All teams played 22 games during the home and away season, for a total of 165. An additional 7 games were played during the finals series.
A team based in the state of South Australia, christened the "[[Adelaide Football Club|Adelaide Crows]]" after the [[epithet]] bestowed upon those from South Australia by those living in other Australian states (viz., the "crow eaters" [http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/crow_eater]) was admitted to the AFL competition in 1991.
{{AFL Ladder/1991}}
==Match attendance== Total match attendance for the home-and-away season was 3,810,868 people. Total attendance for the finals series was 381,707 people. Attendance at the Grand Final was 75,230 people. The largest non-finals attendance was 55,735 people for the {{AFL Mel}} v {{AFL Col}} game of Round 6.
==Awards== *The [[Brownlow Medal]] was awarded to [[Jim Stynes]] of {{AFL Mel}} *The [[Coleman Medal]] was awarded to [[Tony Lockett]] of {{AFL StK}} *The [[Norm Smith Medal]] was awarded to [[Paul Dear]] of {{AFL Haw}} *The [[Leigh Matthews Trophy]] was awarded to [[Jim Stynes]] of {{AFL Mel}} *The Wooden Spoon was "awarded" to {{AFL BB}}
==Notable events== * The [[Adelaide Football Club|Adelaide Crows]] entered the AFL competition. * The [[McIntyre System#McIntyre final five system|McIntyre "Final Five" system]], which had operated from 1972 until 1991, was replaced by the [[McIntyre System#First McIntyre final six system|First McIntyre "Final Six" system]]. The First McIntyre "Final Six" system only lasted a single season. It was replaced by the [[McIntyre System#Second McIntyre final six system|Second McIntyre "Final Six" system]] in 1992. * In Round 6, {{AFL Nor}} and {{AFL Syd}} kicked 32.18 (210) in the first half. It is the only aggregate of 200 points for a half in V/AFL history, and included 18.8 (116) in the second quarter - the second highest aggregate for a quarter. * In Round 11, {{AFL Car}} kicked its only goal through Mark Arceri 33 seconds from the end of their match with [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]]. It was the Blues' lowest score since [[1904 VFL season|1904]], and the closest a team had come to a goalless match since [[1961 VFL season|1961]], when {{AFL Ric}} did not kick a goal against [[St. Kilda Football Club|St. Kilda]]. * In Round 12, {{AFL Foo}} and {{AFL Syd}} played the lowest-scoring draw since 1904. * In Round 22, {{AFL Fit}} and {{AFL Nor}} played the highest-scoring one-point result on record. During this match, North Melbourne became the only team ever to play in one season three quarters with aggregate scores of over 100 points each. * {{AFL WC}} did not concede a century score during the home-and-away season, being the first team to do this since [[1967 VFL season|1967]].
